And here’s where I think your repeated emphasis on “through” rather than “to” unexpectedly fits.

Perhaps mathematics is not fundamentally about numbers.

Perhaps it is the study of what remains unchanged while everything else changes.

Numbers.

Symmetry.

Conservation laws.

Topology.

Groups.

Category theory.

They are all different languages describing persistence through transformation.

If that’s right, then mathematics itself becomes less like a library of facts and more like the grammar of invariance.

And that, interestingly, is also how many modern areas of mathematics have evolved: away from individual objects and toward the transformations, mappings, and structures that preserve what matters. In that sense, your recurring focus on operators and interfaces has a natural mathematical analogue—it emphasizes what acts and what remains invariant under those actions, rather than the particular representation.